            &lt;div class=&quot;comment-body js-comment-edit-hide&quot;&gt;

                &lt;span class=&quot;comment-copy&quot;&gt;@Albin The reason you might want to use &lt;code&gt;std::getline()&lt;/code&gt; is if you want to capture all characters up to a given delimiter and input it into a string, by default that is the newline. If those &lt;code&gt;X&lt;/code&gt; number of strings are just single words/tokens then this job can be easily accomplished with &lt;code&gt;&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt;. Otherwise you would input the first number into an integer with &lt;code&gt;&amp;gt;&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt;, call &lt;code&gt;cin.ignore()&lt;/code&gt; on the next line, and then run a loop where you use &lt;code&gt;getline()&lt;/code&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;

              &lt;div class=&quot;d-inline-flex ai-center&quot;&gt;
